<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Document Profiles Zapatist National Liberation Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0801143394 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0435 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0801143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Socorro Diaz, deputy secretary for civilian 
protection at the Government Secretariat, read today a 28-page 
document with important information on the armed groups that 
have provoked violence in Chiapas State. She said the so-called 
Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] is an extremist 
organization. 
  [Begin Diaz recording, in progress] ...violent, 
professional, 
and well trained. Its profile is highly ideological and uses a 
language that is characteristic of extremist guidelines. [end 
recorded] 
  The armed group includes the participation of ideologists 
and 
clergy; there are medics and transmission technicians, and it is 
comprised of Mexicans and foreigners. Its operation strategy 
for 1993 consisted of advocating the invasion of lands and 
provoking an overall violence. In certain cases it kidnaps 
children to force their parents to join the armed group. 
  Referring to the group's weapons, Diaz said it has machine 
guns, shotguns, revolvers, and sophisticated weapons that are 
suited for guerrilla warfare. The weapons were manufactured 
mainly in the United States, Russia, and the UK. 
  [Begin Diaz recording] The so-called EZLN appeared in 1993 
in five municipalities of Chiapas State--Ocosingo, Las 
Margaritas, Comitan, Altamirano, and Chanal. It has an 
organized network of activists cells that are in permanent 
contact with civilian band radios. It has 15 training centers 
in various municipalities; six of them are located in Las 
Margaritas, five in Ocosingo, two in Sabanillas, one in 
Altamirano, and one in Chanal. [end recording] 
  The report read by Mrs. Socorro Diaz is based on information 
that was provided by the National Defense Secretariat and the 
Attorney General's Office. She said the group has martial arts 
instructors and health promoters. Each squad of activists is 
comprised of one sergeant, one corporal, one radio operator, one 
health promoter, and 20 activists. The group has 172 civilian 
band radio stations in its camps, and authorities have found 
propaganda of the Revolutionary Workers Clandestine People's 
Union Party [Procup], which the group supports by distributing 
its publications. 
  The aggressor group is comprised of and supported by various 
extremist organizations. They have safe houses and assembly 
centers where they show political-revolutionary movies to the 
people. Diaz said many of its leaders have already been 
identified. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

