<H3> <TI>   Rights Activists Turned Back Near San Cristobal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1001150594 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1001150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Samuel Prieto Rodriguez from Chiapas Department; </F>
from the "Good Morning From Mexico" newscast] 
  [Text] The National Network of Civilian Human Rights 
Organizations again tried on Sunday to pass a military roadblock 
outside of San Cristobal de las Casas in an effort to go to 
Ocosingo and Altamirado. On Saturday, the organization had sent 
a letter to National Defense Secretary General Antonio Riviello 
Bazan and 31st Military Garrison Commander Gaston Melchaca, 
informing them of the intention to make the visit based on 
Articles 6 and 11 of the Constitution. 
  [Begin recording of human rights leader Martin Faz, 
indentified by caption] If a legitimate and well-grounded 
impediment exists which would keep us from carrying out this 
objective, please, let us know as soon as possible at the Plaza 
Domingo Hotel, telephone 8-19-27. The above statement is based 
on Article 8 of the Constitution. [end recording] 
  About 16 of the organization's representatives, including 
five from the New York-based Center for Constitutional Rights 
and other U.S. groups, as well as an Indian representative from 
that country, left in two station wagons and headed toward the 
military roadblock located on the road to Rancho Nuevo, followed 
by a motorcade of 50 cars of reporters. At the roadblock, they 
were told to return to San Cristobal to meet with CNDH [National 
Human Rights Committee] Chairman Jorge Madrazo. The press was 
advised to meet with Eloy Cantu Segovia, a senior official of 
the Government Secretariat. These officials would inform them of 
those places to which they are allowed access. 
  In view of this situation, and because they were unable to 
locate Madrazo, the nongovernment groups left in the afternoon 
toward the roadblock on the Tenejapa road. On the way there, 
one of the vehicles ran over an Indian, but fortunately without 
major consequences. 
  There are combat vehicles in midtown San San Cristobal de 
las 
Casas, which are reinforcing military surveillance. Cantu 
Segovia and Madrazo issued no statement on Sunday afternoon. It 
is worth mentioning that the area's military roadblocks do not 
merely consist of tangible objects. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

