<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Not To Participate in European Union Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1101125994 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2213 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1101125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 10 Jan (DPA) -- Costa Rica, the world's 
second largest banana-producing country, will not participate in 
a meeting tomorrow in Brussels summoned by the European Union 
(EU) to discuss with Latin American banana-exporting countries, 
members of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), 
the controversy surrounding regional banana purchases. This is 
how Foreign Trade Minister Roberto Rojas responded today when he 
said that "we already know Europe's position." 
  The meeting was summoned by the EU Executive Commission 
Agriculture Directorate to try to reach an agreement in the 
commercial dispute, which originated with restrictions on Latin 
American banana purchases, effective since July. 
  Latin American countries will meet in San Jose on 13 January 
to try and reach a consensus regarding an EU offer to assign 
quotas to each producing country and 70 percent of the import 
licenses. Most Latin American banana countries object to this 
European initiative. 
  "There is no need for a meeting with the EU, because Costa 
Rica already knows what it will be told," Rojas stated through a 
spokesman. 
  Costa Rica, together with Colombia, has begun negotiations 
regarding the EU initiative and has represented Latin American 
interests before GATT, which was lodged with a lawsuit nearly a 
year ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

