<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 11 January </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201005194 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201005194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments in El Salvador monitored 
through 11 January 1994. Source is cited in parentheses 
following the item. 
  Finance Minister Edwin Sagrera stated that the most 
important 
fiscal events of 1993 were the reduction in the number of taxes 
and the increase in tax collection. Segrera explained that the 
fiscal reform reduced from 25 to three the number of taxes paid 
by Salvadorans. "Currently, there is only the value-added tax 
(VAT), the income tax, and the tax on imports which is paid at 
the Customs Office," he said. He stressed that "despite the 
reduction, tax collection increased thanks to a drop in tax 
evasion." He added that the fiscal deficit, which is 1.8 
percent of the gross national product and which amounts to 1.167 
billion colones, qualifies El Salvador to become a candidate for 
IMF credits. He emphasized that "the deficit can be handled 
indefinitely as long as it is adequately financed." (San 
Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 5 Jan 94 p 12) 

</TEXT>

