<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1101175194 </F>
<F P=103> PA1101175194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Guatemalan economic developments monitored by Panama 
Bureau through 11 January; source follows in parentheses after 
each item. 
  Social Investment Fund (FIS) sources have reported the FIS 
will receive over 270 million quetzals this year through 
contributions from government and international agencies. The 
sources have explained the FIS will receive 50 million quetzals 
from the government, 116 million quetzals from a World Bank 
loan, and 104 million quetzals from the German Development 
Agency. Foreign financing was made possible thanks to the 
executive passing of the regulation on FIS activities. 
(Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 5 Jan 94 p 65) 
  The National Statistics Institute (INE) has reported that 
inflation grew by 11.64 percent in 1993, the level expected by 
government authorities. Inflation grew by 1.31 percent and 1.22 
percent in November and December of 1993, respectively, 
representing a sudden increase in monthly inflation as compared 
to previous months. The government could not meet the objective 
of reducing inflation, which totaled 14.22 percent, by 8 points, 
in 1992. The INE has concluded that the increase in the cost of 
vegetables and fruits in December caused the hike in inflation. 
(Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1758 GMT 5 Jan 94) 
  The Central Bank of Guatemala has reported that as of 30 
September the public foreign debt totaled $2.1 billion. Of this 
amount, $1.5 billion corresponded to the public sector and 
$619.8 million to the Bank of Guatemala. This report cited a 
debt reduction of $124.6 million with respect to 1992, of which 
$85.7 million came from the Bank of Guatemala and $38.9 from the 
public sector. The foreign debt-gross domestic product 
relationship increased from 21.6 percent by the end of 1992 to 
18.7 percent in September of 1993. (Guatemala City EL GRAFICO 
in Spanish 6 Jan 94 p 62) 
  The National Cotton Council director has reported that 
cotton 
production in the country generated $13.9 million in revenues 
during 1993, a 1.7-percent increase with respect to 1992. 
According to cotton producers' estimates, national production 
will disappear in Guatemala within two years. The source 
concluded the decline in international cotton prices has 
continued, forcing several countries out of the market. (Mexico 
City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2357 GMT 6 Jan 94) 
  A study conducted by UNICEF's Social Planning Secretariat 
has 
revealed that 25 percent of the Guatemalan population is 
suffering from poverty. The document has reported that poverty 
is growing 5 percent annually. The study also highlighted the 
low social security coverage in urban areas, which is even worse 
in rural areas. UNICEF has concluded that some 77.6 percent of 
Guatemalan children suffer from some degree of malnutrition. 
(Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1904 GMT 8 Jan 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

