<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sarney, Quercia To Resume Alliance Within PMDB </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1101142294 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 9 
Jan 94 Section 1 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PY1101142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the Brasilia Bureau] </F>
  [Text] Former Sao Paulo State Governor Orestes Quercia 
last week opened the battle against the so-called Gaucho Group 
[from Rio Grande do Sul State] to obtain predominance within the 
PMDB [Brazilian Democratic Movement Party]. The Gaucho Group is 
headed by Pedro Simon (PMDB-RS [PMDB-Rio Grande do Sul State]), 
the government's leader in the Senate. The Gaucho Group 
supports the candidacy of former Social Security Minister 
Antonio Britto in the upcoming presidential elections. 
  The Quercia faction has been strengthened by former 
President 
Jose Sarney's announcement that he will stay in the PMDB. 
Harassed in the PMDB and believing he had lost Quercia's 
support, Sarney had tried to launch his candidacy for president 
through the PP [Popular Party], PFL [Liberal Front Party], PTB 
[Brazilian Labor Party], and even through the PL [Liberal 
Party], but he was not accepted by any of these parties. 
  On 15 January, the Quercia and Sarney factions will resume 
their old alliance and will announce their intention of getting 
the PMDB to break with the government. This was announced 
during a luncheon at Sarney's home. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

