<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201013094 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201013094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Ecuadoran economic developments monitored through 11 
January. The source is cited in parentheses following each item. 
  The National Secretariat for Administrative Development, 
SENDA, reported that during 1993, 25,198 public employees 
stopped working for the government. According to SENDA, the 
state thus reduced its size by reducing appropriations, 
eliminating vacant positions, and not renewing contracts. This 
is part of the effort to modernize the administration. SENDA 
reported that in August 1992 the number of public servants was 
366,227, and by 31 December 1993 the figure dropped to 341,773. 
(Paris AFP in Spanish 2132 GMT 4 Jan 94) 
  The European Union, EU, approved a donation for 
approximately 
$2.8 million to finance social welfare and ecological protection 
programs. An EU spokesman said that the aid will permit the 
implementation of a cholera prevention program to be carried out 
by French experts and Health Ministry officials. He added that 
an ecological evaluation will also be conducted within the 
program on the effects of oil exploitation in the jungle. (Quito 
Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 4 Jan 94) 
  The Ecuadoran State Petroleum Enterprise, Petroecuador, 
announced that a barrel of crude was sold at an average daily 
price of $10.27 in December, thus making the average yearly 
price $14.45 in 1993. In addition, the Energy Ministry reported 
that the 1993 Ecuadoran oil production figure was approximately 
124.8 million barrels, 6 percent more than the preceding year. 
According to provisional figures, average daily production was 
341,700 barrels in 1993 in comparison to 334,400 barrels in 
1992. (Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 4 Jan 94) 
  Petroecuador reported that a new oil well, which initially 
produced 500 barrels per day, was discovered in the Amazon 
region. The well is located near Auca well, eastern Ecuador, 
which accounts for 80 percent of the country's oil production. 
Petroecuador President Federico Veintimilla said that an 
intense exploration program will continue in 1994. (Paris AFP 
in Spanish 1635 GMT 6 Jan 94) 
  Energy and Mines Minister Francisco Acosta stated that 
Texaco 
has filed suit against the Ecuadoran Republic for more than $500 
million. He also said that the government has asked the firm 
for compensation based on technical, tax, and ecological 
reasons. Acosta noted that an agreement could be reached 
relating to Ecuadoran interests and recognition of compensation 
for Ecuador. Rodrigo Perez, the Texaco representative in 
Ecuador, said that an agreement has been reached in principle on 
the technical and tax aspects. With regard to the ecological 
issue, he said that the results of a survey are being reviewed. 
(Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 6 Jan 94) 
  Ecuadoran trade showed a positive balance between January 
and 
October 1993 of $693 million, compared to $745 million for the 
same period in 1992. The Central Bank disclosed that exports 
amounted to $2.4 billion and imports were $1.7 billion in 1993 
compared to $2.5 billion in exports and $1.790 billion in 
imports during the first 10 months of 1992. (Quito Voz de los 
Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 6 Jan 94) 
  President Sixto Duran-Ballen authorized the issuance of 
government bonds for more than $909 million to cover the balance 
of the foreign debt which must be serviced by the country's 
Central Bank. A presidential decree published in the Official 
Registry stated that the bonds will be issued in several 
currencies and will be paid in sucres. This bond issue will be 
used to service the foreign debt with commercial banks, the 
World Bank, and the Export, Import Bank of Japan, the government 
newspaper noted. The Ecuadoran foreign debt amounts to more 
than $12.6 billion. According to the Official Registry, the 
bond issue will allow the government to cover pending balances 
for several credits. (Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 
GMT 11 Jan 94) 
  President Sixto Duran-Ballen authorized the issuance of 
three 
government bonds in sucres for an equivalent of $272.6 million 
to capitalize the Ecuadoran Central Bank, an executive decree 
stated. According to the decree, a bond will be issued for 17.8 
billion sucres, for two years, including a grace period of one 
year, at the basic interest rate that is in effect at the 
beginning of each quarter. The amortization will be made in two 
equal and consecutive biannual quotas that will expire on 30 
June and 31 December 1995. (Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 
2300 GMT 11 Jan 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

