<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tulua Mayor `Upset' Over Search Bloc Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201015594 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1201015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The announcement that the Search Bloc has arrived in 
Valle del Cauca has upset Tulua Mayor Gustavo Alvarez who said 
nobody requested permission from him to house the Search Bloc 
members in that city's police academy. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Mayor Alvarez, 
what 
have you learned about the presence of the Search Bloc here in 
Tulua? 
  [Alvarez] I have no official information on that. Neither 
the national government authorities nor the police authorities 
have notified me that the Search Bloc members will be housed in 
the Simon Bolivar Academy. However, I heard that report in a 
Voice of America broadcast and I read it on the front page of 
today's edition of OCCIDENTE. 
  [Reporter] What does the Search Bloc's arrival represent for 
the residents of Tulua? 
  [Alvarez] As city mayor, I will accept it. However, as a 
resident of Valle del Cauca, I am truly sorry. I have said that 
the Search Bloc in Valle del Cauca is following the orders of 
the U.S. ambassador and State Department officials. Just two 
days after Pablo Escobar was killed, they said that a war had to 
be waged in Valle del Cauca. I think Valle del Cauca does not 
need a war, and I think it can follow the law through reasonable 
means, through a dialogue, and seek solutions so that there will 
be no war here. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

