<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments Through 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201005294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201005294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 11 
January. Source is cited in parentheses following each item. 
  The National Administrative Department of Statistics, DANE, 
reported on 30 December that retail sales rose by 3.7 percent 
from January to October 1993, compared to the same period in 
1992. Furniture and home appliance stores registered a growth of 
14.1 percent in sales. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 
31 Dec 93 p 1C) 
  A report by the National Association of Industrialists, 
ANDI, 
indicated that in 1993 the economy grew at the 5.16 percent rate 
announced by the government. The contribution of the industrial 
sector to this growth was less than 1 percent, meaning the 
Colombian economy in 1993 was marked by low vitality in 
productive activity, it added. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO 
SIGLO in Spanish 31 Dec 94 p 27) 
  A cold spell in Santa Fe de Bogota's savannas destroyed 30 
percent of the areas's flower harvest. In addition to harming 
exports, approximately 26,000 workers will lose their jobs. The 
cold weather also destroyed the potato harvests in Boyaca and 
Cundinamarca Department, the country's chief suppliers. (Santa 
Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 
7 Jan 94) 
  The government granted a 21-percent pay increase to all its 
public officials, except the members of the military and some 
members of the Judicial Branch, who will receive a higher 
increase as part of the strategy to control public order and 
upgrade the system of justice. The increase represents 0.9 
percent of the total production of goods and services of the 
economy or the GDP. The state indicated the raise will not hurt 
its macroeconomic goals because it has been included in the 
estimates for the 1994 budget. During the first half of 1993, 
the state's total spending grew 39 percent, and functioning 
costs rose 46.2 percent. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in 
Spanish 5 Jan 94 pp 1a, 6b) 
  Textile manufacturers have rejected the government 
announcement to lift the port restriction on textile imports and 
proposed a "civic overseer" to assist customs in contraband 
control and detect fraudulent under invoicing. Jose Manuel 
Arias Carrioza, president of the Colombian Association of 
Textile Producers, sent a letter to Pedro Nel Ospina, director 
of the National Customs and Tax Directorate, complaining that 
port controls have slackened. Arias reports that 80 percent of 
Colombian textile factories suffered losses in 1993. The "civic 
overseers" are not intended to check customs work, but to ensure 
that the type of textiles imported do not compete unfairly with 
local production. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 5 Jan 
94 pp 1a, 8b) 
  Colombian coal exports increased 27 percent in 1993 with 
shipments totalling 13.7 millions tons and worth $464 million, 
the Colombian Coal Enterprise, Carbocol, reported. During 1992, 
exports were 2 million tons less than the amount of coal 
produced. Carbocol disclosed that in 1993 production costs were 
reduced by 10 percent from $272 million to $245 million. 
Colombia faced a tough situation during 1993 when world coal 
surpluses topped 11 million tons, thus reducing long term 
contract prices by five dollars per ton. Currently, Colombia 
sells coal at $35 per ton maximum. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in 
Spanish 1735 GMT 7 Jan 94) 
  Housing and food prices were the main culprits for the 
government overshooting its 22 percent inflation rate goal for 
1993. The inflation for 1993 has been reported at 22.6 percent. 
Dane Director Rodolfo Uribe says that the 1.13 percent increase 
in Christmas prices was mainly due to increases in the cost of 
gasoline at the end of the year. Housing costs for December 
reflected the greatest increases and were rated at 1.37 percent 
followed by food that registered a 1.18 percent increase. 
Clothing, health, transportation, and education registered 
below average increases. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL NUEVO SIGLO in 
Spanish 3 Jan 94 pp 1, 9) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

