<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Castro Attends Signing of Colombian Health Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1101151094 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1000 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1101151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Commander in Chief Fidel Castro attended the 
ceremony for the signing of a bilateral cooperation agreement 
between Cuba and Colombia. It was signed by the public health 
ministers of the two countries, Julio Teja and Juan Luis Londono. 
  Fidel briefed the Colombian minister on the characteristics 
of the family doctor program, its origins, and the important 
role it plays in the community. Fidel further pointed out the 
program's contribution in reducing the infant mortality rate to 
9.4 in 1993. He spoke of the training of specialists in general 
medicine, the elevated level of professionalism attained by the 
nurses, and the creation of medical science departments 
throughout the country. 
  The agreement includes prioritized areas such as primary 
attention, epidemiologic surveillance, human resource training, 
essential and generic medicines, and vaccinations. 

</TEXT>

