<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presence of Argentine `Guerrillas' in Chiapas Revolt Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1101153794 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1046 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1101153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 11 Jan (NA) -- Deputy Foreign Minister 
Eduardo Petrella today denied the existence of official 
information on the presence of Argentine guerrillas in the 
National Zapatist Liberation Army (EZLN) in the State of 
Chiapas, Mexico. 
  He thus denied a report published today in a Buenos Aires 
daily which states that "Argentine citizens, who formally 
belonged to the People's Revolutionary Army, are in prominent 
EZLN posts." 
  This information, the newspaper article states, "allegedly 
became available last week in Buenos Aires though secret reports 
prepared by the Mexican Government." 
  According to the article, President Carlos Menem allegedly 
personally referred to the issue when he denounced the existence 
of "subversive mercenaries" in the revolt in the State of 
Chiapas. 
  In statements to a radio station, Petrella said: "We have no 
information" about Argentine guerrillas in Chiapas. 
  The deputy foreign minister said: "Our embassy keeps us 
permanently informed about these things," adding that the 
Mexican problem cannot be "extrapolated" to Argentina. 
  He added that he knows nothing about a possible meeting at a 
continental level to discuss the Mexican problem. The OAS has 
not made any "collective suggestion" on the subject, he said . 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51022 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat008_k_94003" </HT>


