<H3> <TI>   Defense Secretariat Issues Communique </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1101195694 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1900 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1101195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1900 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jaime Guerrero; from the "At Noon" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Defense Secretariat issued a communique a few 
minutes ago reporting on the situation in Chiapas for the last 
few hours. The National Defense communique stated that in the 
town of Guadalupe Tepeyac, the transgressors of the law released 
63 workers of the Social Security clinic who had been kidnapped 
when the conflict began in Chiapas. The workers were taken to 
the Comitan de Dominguez Garrison, where they were fed, and then 
they were sent to the capital of Chiapas State. 
  The Defense Secretariat stated that 10 days after operations 
began to reestablish order in the Chiapas highlands, clashes 
between the transgressors of the law and Army troops have 
decreased considerably. It added that from Monday night to 
early morning Tuesday, there have been no clashes; nevertheless, 
troops are continuing to guard several towns that were the 
targets of the armed groups. The bulletin read that in addition 
to the combing operations by the troops, several aircraft are 
overflying the area to detect the groups of transgressors still 
roaming around some towns. According to the communique, it has 
been learned that approximately 50 transgressors abandoned their 
weapons near Palenque and fled to unknown locations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

