<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Acknowledges Presence of U.S. Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201043194 Paris AFP in Spanish 0346 GMT GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 11 Jan (AFP) -- The Colombian 
Government acknowledged on Tuesday the presence of U.S. troops 
on its national territory, which -- it explained -- "are 
carrying out various tasks within the framework of current 
treaties" signed between the two countries. 
  A press communique issued by the National Defense Ministry 
reported there are 259 U.S. soldiers carrying out different 
tasks in various regions of the country. The official 
communique seeks to calm the strong controversy among country's 
politicians and media over the recent arrival of U.S. Marines in 
the area of the Colombian Pacific area, where -- according to 
the government -- they are participating in the construction of 
civil projects in the poor area of Juanchaco. 

</TEXT>

