<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Misiones Government Reaches `Unique' Agreement With Cuba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0601115194 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 5 Jan 94 
Section 1 p 18--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0601115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Posadas -- Official sources in Posadas have 
announced that a unique exchange will be established between 
Misiones Province and Cuba. 
  The government headed by Fidel Castro will provide free care 
for patients who go to Cuba from Misiones Province to receive 
treatment for eye, spine, skin, respiratory, or other diseases, 
while the island will receive log cabin type housing, corrugated 
cardboard, and liner or Kraft paper manufactured by the Papel 
Misionero factory, owned by the Misiones Government in 
partnership with the Federal Government. 
  To this end a delegation of government officials, headed by 
Governor Federico Ramon Puerta, will go to Havana in late 
January. During his visit the Misiones governor will sign an 
agreement with Castro. 
<H5>  With Other Provinces </H5>
  The Foreign Ministry reported that this type of agreement is 
called a "counterbalanced trade" agreement, and that one 
agreement of this type has already been signed with Rio Negro 
Province. 
  In addition, similar negotiations are currently under way 
between the Cuban Embassy in our country and Entre Rios 
Province. Argentine diplomatic sources reported that the 
governments from other provinces are also interested in these 
agreements. 
  The Caribbean nation has recently signed a training 
agreement 
with Santa Fe Province to provide advanced training for Cuban 
experts on engine mechanics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

