<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   New 1994 Budget Proposal Further Cuts Spending </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0701143794 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
30 Dec 94 p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0701143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- The new version of the 1994 budget, 
which was released yesterday after reformulation of the proposal 
that was submitted to Congress in August, will cause a reduction 
of $12 billion in federal spending with respect to 1993, and a 
$22 billion cut with respect to the first budget bill. The 
revenues and expenditures of the National Treasury will amount 
to $88.8 billion. Planning Ministry Executive Secretary Raul 
Jungman said that the measures will come into force only if 
approved by Congress. "Lawmakers are also responsible for the 
stabilization of the economy, and they will have to decide 
whether we will have a balanced budget, without a deficit." The 
total budget, including debt rescheduling, amounts to $280 
billion. 
  The strict budget proposal establishes that in 1994 
government spending will not surpass revenues, and that public 
debt certificates will be issued only for rescheduling the 
existing domestic and foreign debts. Economist Edmar Bacha, who 
is a special adviser to Finance Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso, said that the budgetary balance is the cornerstone for 
implementation of the second and third stages of the economic 
stabilization program, which involves adoption of the URV [Real 
Value Unit] and its transformation into a strong currency. "We 
are getting rid of the need to balance the budget through 
inflation and corruption. We are exchanging that for 
negotiation, which is the only alternative we have, because the 
other would be a dictatorship." 
  In the new budget bill the government provided for a real 
interest rate of 15 percent for 1994, because no new debts will 
be contracted. This will help reduce payment of interest, which 
will drop from $8.7 billion in 1993 to $7.7 billion in 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

