<H3> <TI>   Moralization Campaign Cuts Public Works Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1001175794 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 9 
Jan 94 p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1001175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As a consequence of the moralization wave that is 
sweeping across the country in the wake of the CPI's 
[Congressional Investigating Committee] discoveries, the cost of 
public works has dropped by almost half. Construction companies 
are now charging much less for their services. The decline in 
costs has prompted the government to study the formation of a 
special commission to renegotiate contracts. With just half the 
allocation to extend the Fernao Dias Highway, which links Belo 
Horizonte with Sao Paulo, it will be possible to finish the job. 
  A high-ranking DNER [National Highway Department] official 
has given another reason for the drop in public works costs: the 
DNER has paid for the contracted services on time, thus 
preventing the overinvoicing by the construction companies. The 
IDB [Inter-American Development Bank] and the World Bank are 
excited with this trend. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

