<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prisoner Exchange Agreement Signed With Colombia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201225394 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1201225394 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Venezuela and Colombia this morning signed a 
bilateral treaty on the repatriation of prison inmates. The 
agreement, proposed by Venezuela, will allow approximately 1,500 
Colombian inmates to return to their country and finish serving 
there the sentences ordered by Venezuelan courts. 
  Eighteen months after the agreement to allow prisoners to go 
to Colombia was presented, Venezuelan Foreign Minister Fernando 
Ochoa Antich and Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin de Rubio 
today signed the final document. 
  The agreement calls for the transfer of prisoners, provided 
they have been sentenced by the courts. Of the 2,800 Colombian 
prisoners in Venezuelan jails, only 1,500 qualify under the 
agreement. Nonetheless, the agreement is voluntary, which means 
that both Venezuelans and Colombians will be able to choose if 
they want to be repatriated or not to their country of origin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51070 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat009_t_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-009 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   President-Elect Caldera To Seek Suspension of VAT </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301003594 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1301003594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President-elect Rafael Caldera has insisted he will 
do everything possible to fulfill his electoral promise of 
suspending the controversial value-added tax [VAT]. 
  Caldera made this statement during a ceremony in his honor 
given by members of the Venezuelan Academy of Language. The 
ceremony was also attended by Venezuelan President Ramon J. 
Velasquez and other representatives from the Executive and 
Judicial Branches. Rafael Caldera pointed out that as soon he 
starts his administration, he will present several proposals to 
the new parliament in an effort to make the VAT more just. 
  [Begin Caldera recording] I hope Congress will accept this. 
I have heard that some groups seem to be interested in learning 
more about my proposal and in accepting it in principle. I hope 
this will be the case. [end recording] 
  When consulted about the possibility of dismissing charges 
against the individuals involved in the massacre at El Amparo, 
the president-elect emphasized that the current government 
should be very careful in this respect. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

