<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister-Designate Discusses Military Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1201131294 Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 27 Dec 93 p C3 </F>
<F P=103> PY1201131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago EL MERCURIO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Defense Minister-designate Edmundo Perez Yoma 
stated on 26 December that the reform of the constitutional 
article that establishes the unremovability of the Armed Forces 
commander in chief is not a priority. 
  Perez Yoma made this remark to a television station. 
  He indicated that it is a question of principles because the 
coalition [Coalition of Parties for Democracy] believes the 
Armed Forces' leadership must be subordinate to civilian 
authorities. But he stated that this type of reform needs a 
broad consensus, and therefore he believes there will be no 
action on the topic in the short term. 
  Perez Yoma said the topic "is neither first nor a priority," 
although he expressed his hope that "we can convince the rest of 
the Chilean people and the Armed Forces" that the power to 
remove the commander in chief must be returned to the president. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

