<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Who Sentenced Guzman Dies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201215494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2103 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201215494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 12 Jan (EFE) -- Peruvian General Jose Picon 
Alcalde, who sentenced Abimael Guzman and Victor Polay, the 
leaders of the Shining Path and the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary 
Movement, respectively, to life in prison, died today with 13 
other high-ranking officers when the helicopter in which they 
were travelling crashed in Cusco. 
  One week ago, General Picon, former chairman of the 4th 
Supreme Council of Military Justice, assumed command of Peru's 
4th Military Region, headquartered in Cusco, a south Andes 
region. According to Radio Programas del Peru Network, the 
tragedy occurred under circumstances that have not been clearly 
explained yet, when the aircraft was overflying Cusco's Velasco 
Astete Airport. 
  According to an initial military report, the helicopter 
crashed for lack of fuel, but witnesses told the radio station 
that the aircraft exploded in the air, before crashing. This 
second version involves the possibility of the incident being a 
terrorist attack. 
  The crash zone, a 200 square meter area over which the 
helicopter debris and bodies of the passengers are spread, has 
been surrounded by troops who are keeping the media away. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

