<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Workers Party, Socialist Party To Sign Alliance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301113294 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
12 Jan 94 p 4--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1301113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- PT [Workers Party] President Luis Inacio 
Lula da Silva and Deputy Miguel Arraes (PE [Pernambuco]), 
president of the PSB [Brazilian Socialist Party], on 11 January 
announced their intention of a coalition for the upcoming 
October general elections. According to Lula da Silva, the 
PT-PSB alliance that will be approved in a few days during a 
meeting of the two parties' executive boards will be a national 
alliance. Lula da Silva said he still does not know who will be 
the ticket's vice presidential candidate for the presidential 
elections, but he praised Senator Jose Paulo Bisol, who was his 
running mate in the 1989 elections. 
  Da Silva said: "I am not the one to choose but Bisol has 
become a better known and consolidated figure in national 
politics." Lula da Silva also said he hopes to attract other 
parties such as the PPS [People's Socialist Party] and the PCdoB 
[Communist Party of Brazil] for a large leftist front but he 
discarded agreements with the PSDB [Brazilian Social Democracy 
Party] and the PDT [Democratic Labor Party], which have their 
own candidates. He said: "[PDT leader Leonel] Brizola has shown 
some repulsion for the PT and said more than once that he is a 
candidate and is not interested in making alliances." 

</TEXT>

