<H3> <TI>   Ghananian Councillor Voices Concerns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301122994 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0013 GMT 11 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1301122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Accra, 10 Jan (PL) -- Captain Kojo Tsikata, member 
of Ghana's Council of State, today voiced his concern over the 
situation in Angola and the future of the ruling party, the 
Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA). 
  During an interview with Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina, the old politician charged that Western governments -- 
without mentioning names -- are exerting pressure to accommodate 
in power Jonas Savimbi, the leader of the armed UNITA [National 
Union for the Total Independence of Angola]. 
  Tsikata criticized the support some governments are still 
giving the Angolan armed rebel group that was defeated in the 
September 1992 first-ever multiparty elections considered valid 
and just by the United Nations. 
  In another part of his conversation with the Cuban foreign 
minister -- who arrived yesterday in this city for an official 
two- day visit -- Tsikata regretted the tensions prevailing in 
Liberia, where Ghana has sent troops to contribute in the search 
for a political solution to the crisis in this West African 
state. 
  Likewise, he encouraged the Nigerian leaders to prevent an 
outbreak of violence in that country. 

</TEXT>

