<H3> <TI>   Robaina, Angolan Counterpart Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401003894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1730 GMT 13 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1401003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Eduardo Rodriguez-Baz] </F>
  [Text] Luanda, 13 Jan (PL) -- Angolan Foreign Minister 
Venacio da Moura affirmed here today that his country views as a 
privilege the fact that the first foreign visitor to Angola in 
1994 has been Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina. 
  At the beginning of official talks between the two leaders 
today, da Moura said that Robaina's visit has taken place at a 
particularly complex moment for the Angolan people because of 
the war being waged by the opposition National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA]. 
  The Angolan minister noted the peace efforts his government 
is making to put an end to the instability produced by the 
domestic conflict, which UNITA rekindled more than one year ago 
after failing in the first multiparty elections. 
  Referring to relations with Cuba, da Moura said that in 
spite 
of difficulties, Angola will work to strengthen the historic 
ties of cooperation with the Caribbean island. 
  Robaina said that his 48-hour visit to this capital forms 
part of a diplomatic offensive in a changing world. Robaina 
stated that the Cuban authorities are working to establish the 
country in the framework in which it belongs. 
  He said: We cannot speak of Cuban diplomacy without 
mentioning Africa and Angola, with which we are united by 
fraternal and traditional ties, in particular, he said. 
  During his first visit to Luanda, the Cuban foreign minister 
has already spoken with the Cuban medical and paramedical 
personnel who work in an important metropolitan hospital and 
plans to meet with Cuban experts in other fields. 
  Today, as part of his busy agenda, Robaina will meet with 
Prime Minister Marcolino Moco and tomorrow he will be received 
by Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos. 
  Robaina will also meet with Franca Van Dunem, president of 
the Angolan Parliament. 
  Angola is Robaina's second stopover in his African journey. 
He has already visited Ghana and will be going to Zimbabwe, 
Zambia, and Namibia. 

</TEXT>

