<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanin To Discuss Case of Downed Venezuelan Helicopter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301183494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1301183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Another of the mandatory issues Foreign Minister 
Noemi Sanin must address while in Venezuela is the case of the 
helicopter in Arauca. The Colombian Prosecutor General's Office 
has enough evidence to press charges against 10 members of the 
Venezuelan National Guard for their part in the border 
incidents. She will not be able to achieve a thing if there is 
no cooperation from Venezuela. 
  The Prosecutor General's Office is investigating four 
specific crimes stemming from the helicopter incident involving 
10 members of the Venezuelan National Guard. The Prosecutor 
General's Office now believes the helicopter was not shot down 
and that the Venezuelan officers violated Colombian territory. 
Theft, property damage, and attempted kidnapping are the other 
crimes under investigation. Given the situation, however, 
Colombia will be unable to act against those responsible as long 
as the Venezuelan Government does not cooperate. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] What will the 
Prosecutor General's Office do next? Are you going to order the 
arrest of those involved? 
  [Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff] Naturally, we will 
have to take measures to take the suspects into custody as well 
as press charges, determine which charges to press, and present 
our cases before the judge. 
  [Reporter] Can these steps be taken by the Colombian 
Prosecutor's Office or will it have to be done by the Venezuelan 
Prosecutor General's Office? 
  [De Greiff] It will have to be done by the Colombian 
prosecutor because the events took place in Colombia. Where we 
do need Venezuela's cooperation -- and we think we will get it 
-- is in identifying the suspects. 
  [Reporter] Would these suspects be brought to Colombia? 
  [De Greiff] Naturally. Again, this would be done with the 
Venezuelan Government's cooperation. [end recording] 
  The issue is now in the hands of Minister Noemi Sanin and 
her 
protest action today in Venezuela, which is directed at getting 
the Venezuelan Government to second Colombia's legal actions and 
seeing these crimes do not go unpunished. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

