<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Files Formal Protest With Venezuela </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401031394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1401031394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Liliana Gutierrez; from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian Government, through Foreign Minister 
Noemi Sanin Posada de Rubio, has filed a formal protest with the 
Venezuelan Government for the violation of its sovereignty by a 
Venezuelan National Guard helicopter in the area of Arauca. 
This is an excerpt of the formal protest note: 
  It textually reads: According to the results of the 
preliminary investigations conducted by the appropriate 
organizations, it has been established that once the aircraft 
illegally entered Colombian territory, its crew began stopping 
and detaining Colombian nationals, mistreating them, and taking 
away their belongings. This is a violation of international and 
internal norms protecting the sovereignty and integrity of 
states and private property. After the incidents mentioned 
above, the Colombian nationals who were being held were forced 
to board the helicopter that later crashed, injuring some of 
them. 
  The formal protest note adds: The Colombian Government, in 
condemning these incidents, is attentively awaiting the results 
of the investigation. It hopes the results will enable 
authorities to determine who was responsible, as well as to 
impose severe punishment on those responsible in order to avoid 
situations in the future that could tarnish the existing 
atmosphere of understanding between our peoples and governments. 
  Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin will turn over to the 
Venezuelan 
Government the protest on the violation of Colombian airspace 
and territory following the incident with the Venezuelan 
National Guard helicopter, which crashed in the Puerto Rico area 
in Arauca Department. The foreign minister asked authorities to 
investigate and punish those found responsible for abuses 
committed against peasants in the region. 
  Even though the diplomatic language was one of mutual praise 
and the incident was played down, Colombia gave the Venezuelan 
authorities the evidence gathered by the Prosecutor General's 
Office and the Defense Ministry. 
  Meanwhile, Venezuelan Defense Minister Radames Munoz said 
the 
incident was due to mechanical problems with the helicopter and 
added that Colombian sovereignty was not violated and peasants 
were not mistreated. 
  Finally, there was a border commission meeting in Caracas. 
Members reviewed the report drafted by Deputy Pompeyo Marquez in 
which it was revealed that along the 2,000-km border there are 
more than 70 areas where conflicts have occurred. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

