<H3> <TI>   Staff Chief Reiterates Military Subordination to Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301195894 Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA in Spanish 7 Jan 
94 p 14 </F>

<F P=103> PY1301195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago LA TERCERA DE LA HORA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hernan Garcia M-C] </F>
  [Excerpt] Vice Admiral Jorge Patricio Arancibia, chief of 
the National Defense Staff, yesterday reiterated that the 
Chilean Armed Forces "are totally subordinated to the 
government, and should they undertake any action they will do it 
with top professionalism." 
  During a Latin American seminar on military spending being 
held in Santiago, Arancibia made an overall analysis of the 
decisionmaking process and changes within this context. He 
emphasized that this type of meeting permitted one to see "the 
progress achieved in technical and academic relations between 
civilians and the military." 
  During the conference's first day, which was designed by the 
National Academy of Political and Strategic Studies [Academia 
Nacional de Estudios Politicos y Estrategicos] (ANEPE), and by 
the Latin American School of Social Sciences (Flacso), the 
agenda included defense policies, new security concepts, the 
economic balance, and military spending in developed countries. 
[passage omitted] 

