<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   FMLN Reiterates Impartiality in Chiapas Incidents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301123394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0038 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1301123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 12 Jan (EFE) -- El Salvador's Farabundo 
Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN) today, Wednesday, 
rejected in the Mexican capital any insinuation that attempts to 
implicate it in the Chiapas conflict. Incidents in Chiapas "are 
strictly internal problems of the Mexican state," and solutions 
should be reached while respecting Mexico's sovereignty, 
indicated the FMLN in a press communique sent to EFE. 
  The former Salvadoran guerrillas expressed their support for 
the peace initiatives through dialogue between all the sectors 
involved and regretted the loss of human lives in the armed 
conflict. 
  The FMLN reiterated that since the signing of the 
Chapultepec 
Agreement in January 1993, it is a completely legal political 
party, respecting noninterference in the internal affairs of 
third countries. 
  The former guerrillas condemned press and political 
statements linked to the ARENA [Nationalist Reublican Alliance] 
party that attempt to tangle the FMLN in the violent Chiapas 
incidents. They warned that these accusations are evidence of 
despair in the face of the FMLN's electoral progress with regard 
to the March 1994 Salvadoran elections. 

</TEXT>

