<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Terrorist Resurgence Prompts `State of Alert' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301210694 Asuncion ULTIMA HORA in Spanish 13 Jan 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> PY1301210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ULTIMA HORA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by correspondent Dolores Oliveira in Buenos Aires] </F>
  [Text] Argentine President Carlos Menem yesterday ordered a 
"state of alert" among Argentine intelligence services in light 
of the possibility of a subversive resurgence -- like the 
uprising in Chiapas, Mexico -- in Southern Cone countries. The 
president caught his main security assistants by surprise. They 
attributed the initiative to Menem's "intuition." There were 
rumors that everything began after closed door conversations 
with Uruguayan President Luis Alberto Lacalle and Paraguayan 
President Juan Carlos Wasmosy in Punta del Este, Uruguay, last 
week. According to reports published in Buenos Aires by the 
morning economic newspaper EL CRONISTA, Argentine officials who 
accompanied Menem in Punta del Este detected a fear -- 
particularly among members of Wasmosy's entourage -- of 
"hit-and-run forays" across Paraguayan and Bolivian borders by 
-- as Paraguayan politicians put it -- "narcoterrorists at the 
service of the Sao Paulo forum." 
<H5>  The Sao Paulo Forum </H5>
  The so-called Sao Paulo Forum was born in 1990 in the wake 
of 
a well-intentioned initiative by labor leader Luiz Inacio "Lula" 
da Silva to unify the Latin American leftist sectors and to lead 
them along the path of democracy, consensus, and government 
experience. 
  The Forum has already held four subsequent meetings, in Sao 
Paulo, Mexico, Managua, and Havana. Two irreconcilable 
positions emerged from within the Forum at the latest meeting in 
Havana. On the one hand, those who insisted on the political 
course. Among them were the Uruguayan Broad Front; the 
Brazilian labor movement; and Mexico's opposition PRD [Party of 
the Democratic Revolution], led by political scientist Jorge 
Castaneda -- the philosophical inspirer of this Latin American 
leftist group. On the other hand, the hardliners refuse to give 
up the armed struggle and who decided "to prepare for a 
rebellion by the victims of the economic adjustment." This 
happened just two months ago, in November 1993. 
  An intelligence report read a few hours ago by President 
Menem suggests some irregularities that might include a 
connection among the various attempts to begin subversive 
activities in Argentine territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

