<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Discusses Santiago del Estero Unrest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301165094 Buenos Aires LA PRENSA in Spanish 11 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PY1301165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Interior Minister Carlos Ruckauf while </F>
vacationing in Villa Gesel by "special correspondent" Norberto 
Beladrich; date not given] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] [Beladrich] Everyone is still 
very well aware of what happened in Santiago del Estero, 
surely... 
  [Ruckauf] I am convinced that Santiago del Estero has not 
been a "victim" of the transformation process. What should have 
been done there was just not done. There was a chaotic 
government, very bad mismanagement of the economy, and an 
astronomical financial crisis. 
  [Beladrich] For you then Santiago del Estero is a unique 
case? 
  [Ruckauf] I did not say that; but it is very different from 
the rest because all the ingredients were right for an 
explosion. Think back to January 1993, the salary roster 
amounted to 20 million pesos; in October it escalated to 36 
million pesos, while income amounted to some 5 million pesos... 
Other provinces have problems regarding the income-expenditure 
ratio, but no province had such a bad ratio as Santiago del 
Estero. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

