<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Changes Sought by Northwestern Provinces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301133694 Buenos Aires CLARIN in Spanish 12 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PY1301133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires CLARIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The economy ministers of the northwestern Argentine 
provinces agreed on 11 January in Tucuman on "the need to adapt 
the public sector's national reform policy to the provinces' 
reality." Since the people's revolt in Santiago del Estero, this 
is the first sign of alert made jointly in disagreement with 
Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo. 
  The meeting was attended by the economy ministers of 
Tucuman, 
Raul Paulino Rios; Catamarca, Herman Colombo; and Jujuy, Daniel 
Gomar; La Rioja Finance Secretary Pablo Manuel Aguilera; and 
Salta Public Works Secretary Julio Guzman. 
  The meeting was not attended by the representative of 
Santiago del Estero, where the revolt took place and whose 
government has been intervened by the federal government. 
  After analyzing the social conflicts that are nearly 
permanent in their respective provinces, the growing 
unemployment in the public sector, and the recent demonstrations 
staged by tobacco workers, the ministers drafted a critical 
diagnosis of the consequences of the national economic policy. 
At the meeting's end they released a short communique. 
  The most important paragraph of the joint declaration states 
"the need to adapt the public sector's national reform policy to 
the provinces' reality." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

