<H3> <TI>   Government Considers Canadian Wheat Import `Closed' Matter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1401020594 Buenos Aires CLARIN in Spanish 13 Jan 94 p 23 </F>
<F P=103> PY1401020594 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires CLARIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo -- The case of the 1-million-ton shipment 
of Canadian wheat that will enter Brazil from Canada at a very 
low price is closed. Argentina has asked Brazil for 
"compensation" to its growers to counterbalance the "unfair 
competition" from the Canadians. The Itamar Franco government 
has, however, already made its decision: "The state does not 
intervene in the grain market, which is absolutely free." 
  In a conversation with CLARIN, Foreign Trade Secretary 
Renato 
Marques said: "As of 1991, wheat purchases are no longer 
handled by the state. Today private parties freely import 
wheat. Brazil no longer exercises foreign trade control." 
  [CLARIN] There was the situation when Brazil granted 
Argentina compensation after confirming that U.S. wheat sold to 
Brazil was subsidized... 
  [Marques] That was an entirely different case. The United 
States was exporting wheat under the Export Enhancement Program, 
and this involved oficial recognition that wheat was being 
subsidized. 

</TEXT>

