<F P=100> Grenada </F>
<F P=101> St. Vincent and the Grenadines </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Trade Minister Named </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1301212294 Bridgetown CANA in English 2010 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL1301212294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kingstown, St. Vincent, 13 Jan, CANA -- St Vincent 
and the Grenadines minister of trade and consumer affairs, 
Johnathan Peters, has been relieved of his ministry and placed 
on leave until month-end, Prime Minister James Mitchell has 
announced. 
  Mitchell, in a statement released by the Government 
Information Service, said Peters, who has been in the United 
States since early December, will now be a minister without 
portfolio while Bernard Wyllie, formerly parliamentary secretary 
in the Communications and Works Ministry, takes over the Trade 
Ministry. 
  Wyllie was sworn in midday Thursday as trade and consumer 
affairs minister. 
  Mitchell said Peters had asked for an extension of time to 
conduct urgent personal business in the US after he had 
concluded official business there last October. 
  Peters is said to be sorting out problems with the US 
Immigration and Naturalisation Service and Mitchell said 
although he was assured Peters would be returning home it was 
apparent he was not likely to return soon. 
  "When his leave is up, I will address the matter further," 
Mitchell said. 
  Peters, a former ambassador to the United Nations, was 
brought home to contest the 1989 general election and won the 
north central Windward seat for the ruling New Democratic Party, 
which took all 15 seats. 
  Mitchell said he had asked the north central Windward 
parliamentary representative, Allan Cruickshank, and his north 
Windward colleague, Monty Roberts, to see after Peters' 
constituency "for the time being." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

