<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Unionist Believes U.S. Measures Not To Affect Brazil </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1401114094 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 10 Jan 
94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PY1401114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The "feud" between the United States and the PRC 
should not affect Brazilian businesses, even though the United 
States is the number one importer of Brazilian products. Luiz 
Americo Medeiros, the chairman of the Textile Industry Trade 
Union (Sinditextil), has stated that "when the United States 
cuts the quota of one country it does not necessarily increases 
that of another. On the contrary, it increasingly seeks to 
apply more restrictions." Medeiros noted that the United States 
finds it easy to curtail the PRC's quota because the latter has 
not yet joined the GATT. The bilateral agreement between Brazil 
and the United States expires on 31 March and will be 
automatically renewed for another year. 

</TEXT>

