<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Geneva Representative Examines Advantages of GATT Approval </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1301192394 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
12 Jan 94 p B10 </F>

<F P=103> PY1301192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Aldo Renato Soares] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia -- Luiz Felipe Lampreia, Brazilian 
representative before the international organizations 
headquartered in Geneva (Switzerland), yesterday said that 
Brazil can benefit from a tariff reduction in the U.S. and 
European markets. Up until 12 April -- when the ceremony for 
the final signing of the Uruguay Round of the GATT (General 
Agreement on Trade and Tariffs) talks will be held in Marrakesh, 
Morocco -- tariffs may not be increased. Lampreia, Brazil's top 
negotiator in the Uruguay Round, denied that the Brazilian 
agricultural sector was harmed by the negotiations. 
  "Brazil did not win, but is not worse off than it was," he 
said. In making an evaluation of the Uruguay Round, Lampreia 
admitted that the liberalization of trade for industrial 
products was more comprehensive than it was for agricultural 
products. "Negotiations over farm products are always more 
complicated," he emphasized. Lampreia said that Brazil could 
still obtain tariff reductions in the U.S. and European markets, 
especially on orange juice. The United States reduced tariffs on 
orange juice by 15 percent, and the Europeans by 20 percent. 
  Lampreia explained that the greatest progress made in the 
Uruguay Round was represented by the agreement on the rules that 
will ban the adoption of unilateral, arbitrary, antidumping 
measures. "The margin of arbitrariness will be considerably 
reduced," he said, adding that after the ceremony in Marrakesh, 
which will be attended by the foreign ministers of 117 
countries, the agreements signed in Geneva will be translated 
and sent to each signatory country. The Senate Economic Affairs 
Committee will begin studying the agreements by mid-May. 
  Lampreia said that there are no possibilities for any 
modifications. "Either the Senate approves them or rejects 
them," he noted. At the beginning of 1995, GATT will host a 
ministerial conference to evaluate the approval of the 
agreements, and will start the work for the creation of the 
International Organization of Commerce, which will replace GATT. 
Lampreia said the new organization will begin operating in July 
1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

