<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Various Sectors Greet Cease-Fire Initiative </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301222194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1719 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1301222194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 13 Jan (EFE) -- Various Mexican 
political and intellectual sectors welcomed President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari's decision to order a cease-fire in the 
southern State of Chiapas to encourage dialogue with the rebel 
forces. 
  Presidential candidates for the Institutional Revolutionary 
Party (PRI), National Action Party (PAN), and the Party of the 
Democratic Revolution (PRD) viewed the announcement of an Armed 
Forces unilateral truce with satisfaction. 
  Luis Donaldo Colosio, PRI presidential candidate in the 
upcoming August elections, stressed that what is important at 
this moment is that the Indians' human rights and lives be 
respected. In an allusion to Chiapas, he also hoped "that this 
cease-fire will be permanent so that we can find peaceful 
solutions to the problems that afflict this area that is so dear 
to Mexicans." 
  PRD presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas said that the 
cease-fire is only the first step that should be taken to 
reestablish peace and recommended that both sides "confine to 
quarters" their troops to achieve conditions for dialogue. "What 
should be done now is to declare amnesty for everyone, release 
prisoners, guarantee medical attention for the wounded, and 
appoint a governor who has the backing and consensus of the 
people of Chiapas," added Cardenas. The unilateral truce 
announcement was, according to Cardenas, the result of pressure 
exerted by various sectors of society that had demanded a rapid 
political solution to the conflict. 
  PAN (the country's second electoral force) presidential 
candidate Diego Fernandez de Cevallos believes that Salinas de 
Gortari has made a "sensible decision," a decision that all 
political groups agreed with from the beginning. Likewise, he 
wants conditions rapidly established that will solve the root 
cause of the insurrection, such as attention to the historical 
problems of the area and many others "where bullets have not 
talked." Fernandez de Cevallos called on his electoral rivals to 
"abstain from actions and behavior that in some way could imply 
opportunism or be offensive to the people of Chiapas and society 
in general." 
  The Permanent Agrarian Congress, which groups together 11 
peasant organizations, gave its support to the president's 
decision and defined it as "a firm step to attain peace." 
  Saul Gonzalez, chairman of the Grand Commission of the 
Senate, believes that the dialogue between the insurgent 
Zapatist National Liberation Army (EZLN) and the government will 
have to take place under conditions of equality and flexibility. 
In addition, he said, the bases should be laid so that the 
rebels can reenter national political life with the political 
party that best responds to their beliefs. 
  Political expert Pablo Gonzalez Casanova said that it is a 
mistake to think that the Chiapas conflict can be resolved in 
the short term, although he believes that the government decreed 
cease- fire is a positive event in the search of peace. 
Gonzalez, who is in Ocosingo, one of the villages most affected 
by the clashes, said that the recent cabinet changes show that 
at last there have been deeds rather than words in Mexico. 
  Monday's government changes included the dismissal of 
Government Secretary Patrocinio Gonzalez Blanco and the 
appointment of Manuel Camacho Solis, up to now foreign 
secretary, to the post of peace and reconciliation commissioner 
to Chiapas. 
  According to various analysts, President Salinas de 
Gortari's 
decision to decree a cease-fire is the first concrete step to 
act politically in the Chiapas armed conflict, abandoning the 
military option after proving its uselessness in resolving the 
crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

