<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Relations To Be Resumed With Canada </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401022894 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1401022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Canada will resume bilateral relations with Peru, 
which were suspended on 5 April 1992. The announcement was made 
by Christine Stewart, the Canadian minister of state for Latin 
America and Africa. 
  At a news conference the ranking Canadian official said that 
her trip to Peru has allowed her to confirm the current 
situation in the country. She said she is pleased with the 
progress the country has made in the area of economics and 
especially in the area of human rights. She pointed out that 
the Canadian Government is willing to resume bilateral relations 
with Peru, which were interrupted following the self-inflicted 
coup on 5 April 1992, and to resume providing social aid for 
extremely poor sectors of the population. 
  [Begin Stewart recording] Our presence in Peru, which has 
always remained at the same levels in the past, focuses on 
programs to provide aid especially for the poor of this country. 
Overall human development and sustained growth are priorities 
for my government. [end recording] 
  Christine Stewart said that Canadian businessmen are quite 
interested in investing in Peru which, evidently, would 
contribute to the country's development. 
  [Begin Stewart recording] Private Canadian businessmen can 
also invest here for the improvement of Peru and also to 
maintain advantages for Canada. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

