<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Rejection of Human Rights-Trade Link Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1301174894 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1503 GMT 
13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1301174894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] PRC Foreign Ministry spokesman (Hu Hiangming) has 
affirmed that it is up to the Chinese people alone to comment on 
the human rights situation in the PRC. The Chinese Government, 
in this way, responded sharply to reports from officials in 
Washington who link trade between the two countries to the 
internal situation of the PRC. The United States has reduced to 
35 percent its imports of textiles from China, and now there is 
talk at the White House of withdrawing China's trade status as a 
Most Favored Nation, according to a report from PRENSA LATINA. 
  Business is business, stressed the Foreign Ministry 
spokesman, recalling that the PRC has achieved remarkable 
successes since it was founded in 1949, especially with the 
reforms put into practice in the past 15 years -- which has been 
acknowledged internationally. 

</TEXT>

