<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazil's Franco Speaks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1801000894 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2100 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1801000894 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During the fifth Common Market of the South 
[Mercosur] summit in Colonia del Sacramento, Uruguay, President 
Itamar Franco stressed that this year Mercosur will have to 
define a foreign tariff and the common trade policy that will be 
pursued. 
  Sitting next to the presidents of Argentina, Uruguay, and 
Paraguay, the Brazilian president emphasized that Mercosur's 
success will be closely linked to the customs unification on 1 
January 1995. 
  President Itamar Franco stressed that the Brazilian 
Government is determined to comply with all the commitments made 
in order to implement the economic and social goals defined in 
the Asuncion Treaty. 
  In his speech, President Itamar Franco emphasized that 
Brazil 
does not assign an exclusive priority to Mercosur and confirmed 
his favorable stance for enhancement and joint efforts toward 
integration with the Andean Group and Amazon Initiative 
countries. 
  In his speech, the Brazilian president said the Mercosur 
countries are paying attention to today's reality involving the 
establishment of NAFTA, an organization economically uniting the 
United States, Mexico, and Canada. 
  President Itamar Franco emphasized the democratic maturity 
of 
Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, and Paraguay as a factor required 
for the success of South America's integration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

