<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Human Rights Committee on Canal Employees, Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1701035894 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 16 
Jan 94 p B5 </F>

<F P=103> PA1701035894 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Communique issued by the Panamanian Human Rights Committee; </F>
place and date not given] 
  [Text] The Panamanian Human Rights Committee (CPDH) hereby 
addresses the nation and especially canal area employees to 
outline its position concerning the recent assertions made by 
the Panama Canal administrator regarding the political 
participation of canal employees in the upcoming elections in 
May 1994. 
  First, it is worth explaining that the reasons invoked by 
the canal administration to justify the ban on Panama Canal 
employees' participation in the May elections are applicable 
only to U.S. citizens. To attempt to impose them on Panamanians 
is to disregard the basic principles of national sovereignty. 
  Second, Panama's Constitution acknowledges the basic right 
to 
elect others and be elected to public office. A foreign law 
cannot infringe on precepts established in the laws of the 
nation. 
  Third, the canal administrator's assertions are not in 
keeping with international pledges signed by the Republic of 
Panama by way of important human rights pacts and international 
agreements. Article 25 of the International Pact on Civil and 
Political Rights establishes that all citizens will enjoy the 
right to participate in the conduction of public affairs 
directly or through freely elected representatives. 
  Due to all of the above, the CPDH reaffirms the canal area 
employees' inalienable right to participate fully in the 
nation's politics. 
  Panamanian Human Rights Committee 
  [signed] Roberto Troncoso B., president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51250 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat011_j_94009" </HT>


