<F P=100> Guyana </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Assembly Passes Bill on CET Rates </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1501184394 Bridgetown CANA in English 1656 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL1501184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgetown, Guyana, 15 Jan, CANA -- Guyana's 
National Assembly has passed a customs amendment bill comprising 
new rates of the Caribbean Community (Caricom) Common External 
Tariff [CET] , being implemented by the community's 12-member 
common market. 
  Guyana is one of three member states -- Antigua and Barbuda, 
and Montserrat are the others -- yet to implement the CET after 
Caricom agreement in 1992 on a lowering of the tariffs to 
reflect international trends. 
  All three opposition parties here supported the government 
as 
the Customs (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 1993 came up for debate and 
passage this week. Debate on the bill was previously scheuled 
for December 16, but was postponed because of delays in printing 
of the voluminous tariff rates. 
  The CET is intended to demarcate a regional market behind a 
common tariff against third-country goods. It is expected to 
facilitate the development of regional manufacturing and 
agriculture. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

