<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mayor Cites Weapons Brought by U.S. Troops in Juanchaco </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1601030994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0132 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1601030994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Magnolia Ruiz; from the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The gringos that are camped out in Juanchaco have 
certainly brought weapons, reported Tulua Mayor Gustavo Alvarez 
Gardeazabal today. They have enough weaponry to seize half of 
Colombia, he said. 
  [Begin Alvarez recording] The U.S. presence is a presence of 
foreign troops. Those people brought weapons, but Admiral Jose 
Ignacio Rozo [commander of the National Navy Base at Malaga Bay] 
has their weapons stored in a container that is under the 
custody of a Colombian soldier. The admiral is executing strict 
orders based on an agreement, but a foreign Army is undoubtedly 
being lodged at a Colombian naval base; therefore, it was 
necessary to request the Senate's permission. [end recording] 
  The great doubt of why prevails. What is the reason? What 
explanation will be given concerning a large weapons shipment 
under the custody of a Colombian Navy member if they reportedly 
came to cooperate with Colombia and build projects in the zone? 
  [Begin Alvarez recording] I met with a commission from the 
Prosecutor General's Office, which is investigating the case. I 
suppose the same will be done by the commissions being sent this 
week by Valle Department's assembly, Buenaventura's council, the 
Senate of the Republic, and many journalists from different 
media, who will witness how enough weapons to seize half of 
Colombia were transferred to build a small school and a health 
post. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

