<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Continues To Seize Venezuelan Weapons From Guerrillas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1601150294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1601150294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "NTC" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Weapons of the Venezuelan Armed Forces continue to 
fall into the hands of Colombian guerrillas. Here is evidence: 
Troops of the 7th Brigade headquartered in Villavicencio seized 
an FAL assault rifle, the regulation weapon of the Venezuelan 
military, from the FARC [Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]. 
  The guerrillas repainted the rifle to hide its origin, but 
under the paint an inscription can still be read: Venezuelan 
Armed Forces. 
  There are 80 other rifles like this one in Villavicencio, 
not 
counting the ones seized in other areas of the country. 
  Venezuelan Military Staff members will arrive in Bucaramanga 
on 18 January to request the return of a large number of 
Venezuelan weapons seized from several guerrilla fronts. 
  The official Venezuelan explanation continues to be that the 
weapons were stolen from border garrisons. 
  The Colombian and Venezuelan defense ministers will meet on 
19 January here at the 5th Brigade headquarters in Bucaramanga 
to study the issue of Venezuelan weapons in the hands of 
Colombian guerrillas. 
  In dealing blows to the Colombian guerrillas over the last 
few months, authorities have found Venezuelan assault rifles, 
mortars, ammunition, and submachine guns, all of which bear the 
coat of arms and insignia of the Venezuelan Armed Forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

